# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vxworks-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vxworks-deep/board-support-package] The board support package is usually provided by the SoC manufacturer (such as Qualcomm), and may be modified by the OEM.
[src:vxworks-deep/board-support-package] Third-party hardware developers who wish to support a given embedded operating system must create a BSP that allows that embedded operating system to run on their platform.
[src:vxworks-deep/board-support-package] In most cases, the embedded operating system image—containing the BSP, software license, and hardware support—is bundled together by the hardware vendor.
[src:vxworks-deep/board-support-package] BSPs are typically customizable, allowing the user to specify which drivers and routines should be included in the build based on their selection of hardware and software options.
[src:vxworks-deep/board-support-package] For instance, a particular single-board computer might be paired with several peripheral chips; in that case the BSP might include drivers for peripheral chips supported; when building the BSP image the user would specify which peripheral drivers to include based on their choice of hardware.
[src:vxworks-deep/board-support-package] Some suppliers also provide a root file system, a toolchain for building programs to run on the embedded system, and utilities to configure the device (while running) along with the BSP.
[src:vxworks-deep/board-support-package] Many embedded operating system providers provide template BSP's, developer assistance, and test suites to aid BSP developers to set up an embedded operating system on a new hardware platform.
[src:vxworks-deep/board-support-package] The term *BSP* has been in use since 1981 when Hunter & Ready, the developers of the Versatile Real-Time Executive (VRTX), first coined the term to describe the hardware-dependent software needed to run VRTX on a specific hardware platform.
[src:vxworks-deep/board-support-package] Since the 1980s, it has been in wide use throughout the industry.
[src:vxworks-deep/board-support-package] Virtually all RTOS providers now use the term BSP.
[src:vxworks-deep/board-support-package] In modern systems, the term has been extended to refer to packages that only deal with one processor, not the whole motherboard.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] An **embedded system** is a specialized computer system—a combination of a computer processor, computer memory, and input/output peripheral devices—that has a dedicated function within a larger mechanical or electronic system.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] It is embedded as part of a complete device, often including electrical or electronic hardware and mechanical parts.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems control many devices in common use.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In 2009, it was estimated that 98% of all microprocessors manufactured were used in embedded systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Because an embedded system typically controls physical operations of the machine that it is embedded within, it often has real-time computing constraints.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Modern embedded systems are often based on microcontrollers (i.e., microprocessors with integrated memory and peripheral interfaces), but ordinary microprocessors (using external chips for memory and peripheral interface circuits) are also common, especially in more complex systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In either case, the processor(s) used may be types ranging from general purpose to those specialized in a certain class of computations, or even custom designed for the application at hand.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] A common standard class of dedicated processors is the digital signal processor (DSP).
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Since the embedded system is dedicated to specific tasks, design engineers can optimize it to reduce the size and cost of the product and increase its reliability and performance.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are mass-produced, benefiting from economies of scale.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems range in size from portable personal devices such as digital watches and MP3 players to bigger machines like home appliances, industrial assembly lines, robots, transport vehicles, traffic light controllers, and medical imaging systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Often they constitute subsystems of other machines like avionics in aircraft and astrionics in spacecraft.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Large installations like factories, pipelines, and electrical grids rely on multiple embedded systems networked together.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Generalized through software customization, embedded systems such as programmable logic controllers frequently comprise their functional units.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The origins of the microprocessor and the microcontroller can be traced back to the MOS integrated circuit, which is an integrated circuit chip fabricated from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors) and was developed in the early 1960s.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] By 1964, MOS chips had reached higher transistor density and lower manufacturing costs than bipolar chips.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to large-scale integration (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS chip by the late 1960s.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The application of MOS LSI chips to computing was the basis for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete computer processor system could be contained on several MOS LSI chips.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released in 1971.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] One of the first recognizably modern embedded systems was the Apollo Guidance Computer, developed ca.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] 1965 by Charles Stark Draper at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] At the project's inception, the Apollo guidance computer was considered the riskiest item in the Apollo project as it employed the then newly developed monolithic integrated circuits to reduce the computer's size and weight.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] An early mass-produced embedded system was the Autonetics D-17 guidance computer for the Minuteman missile, released in 1961.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] When the Minuteman II went into production in 1966, the D-17 was replaced with a new computer that represented the first high-volume use of integrated circuits.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Since these early applications in the 1960s, embedded systems have come down in price and there has been a dramatic rise in processing power and functionality.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] An early microprocessor, the Intel 4004 (released in 1971), was designed for calculators and other small systems but still required external memory and support chips.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] By the early 1980s, memory, input and output system components had been integrated into the same chip as the processor, forming a microcontroller.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Microcontrollers find applications where a general-purpose computer would be too costly.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] As the cost of microprocessors and microcontrollers fell, the prevalence of embedded systems increased.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] A comparatively low-cost microcontroller may be programmed to fulfill the same role as a large number of separate components.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] With microcontrollers, it became feasible to replace, even in consumer products, expensive knob-based analog components such as potentiometers and variable capacitors with up/down buttons or knobs read out by a microprocessor.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Although in this context an embedded system is usually more complex than a traditional solution, most of the complexity is contained within the microcontroller itself.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Very few additional components may be needed and most of the design effort is in the software.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Software prototype and test can be quicker compared with the design and construction of a new circuit not using an embedded processor.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems are commonly found in consumer, industrial, automotive, home appliances, medical, telecommunication, commercial, aerospace and military applications.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Telecommunications systems employ numerous embedded systems from telephone switches for the network to cell phones at the end user.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Computer networking uses dedicated routers and network bridges to route data.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Consumer electronics include MP3 players, television sets, mobile phones, video game consoles, digital cameras, GPS receivers, and printers.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Household appliances, such as microwave ovens, washing machines and dishwashers, include embedded systems to provide flexibility, efficiency and features.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Advanced heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems use networked thermostats to more accurately and efficiently control temperature that can change by time of day and season.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Home automation uses wired and wireless networking that can be used to control lights, climate, security, audio/visual, surveillance, etc., all of which use embedded devices for sensing and controlling.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Transportation systems from flight to automobiles increasingly use embedded systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] New airplanes contain advanced avionics such as inertial guidance systems and GPS receivers that also have considerable safety requirements.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Spacecraft rely on astrionics systems for trajectory correction.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Various electric motors — brushless DC motors, induction motors and DC motors — use electronic motor controllers.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Automobiles, electric vehicles, and hybrid vehicles increasingly use embedded systems to maximize efficiency and reduce pollution.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Other automotive safety systems using embedded systems include anti-lock braking system (ABS), electronic stability control (ESC/ESP), traction control (TCS) and automatic four-wheel drive.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Medical equipment uses embedded systems for monitoring, and various medical imaging (positron emission tomography (PET), single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) for non-invasive internal inspections.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems within medical equipment are often powered by industrial computers.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems are used for safety-critical systems in aerospace and defense industries.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Unless connected to wired or wireless networks via on-chip 3G cellular or other methods for IoT monitoring and control purposes, these systems can be isolated from hacking and thus be more secure.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] For fire safety, the systems can be designed to have a greater ability to handle higher temperatures and continue to operate.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In dealing with security, the embedded systems can be self-sufficient and be able to deal with cut electrical and communication systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Miniature wireless devices called motes are networked wireless sensors.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] These motes are completely self-contained and will typically run off a battery source for years before the batteries need to be changed or charged.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems are designed to perform a specific task, in contrast with general-purpose computers designed for multiple tasks.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Some have real-time performance constraints that must be met, for reasons such as safety and usability; others may have low or no performance requirements, allowing the system hardware to be simplified to reduce costs.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems are not always standalone devices.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Many embedded systems are a small part within a larger device that serves a more general purpose.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] For example, the Gibson Robot Guitar features an embedded system for tuning the strings, but the overall purpose of the Robot Guitar is to play music.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Similarly, an embedded system in an automobile provides a specific function as a subsystem of the car itself.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The program instructions written for embedded systems are referred to as firmware, and are stored in read-only memory or flash memory chips.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] They run with limited computer hardware resources: little memory, small or non-existent keyboard or screen.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems range from no user interface at all, in systems dedicated to one task, to complex graphical user interfaces that resemble modern computer desktop operating systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Simple embedded devices use buttons, light-emitting diodes (LED), graphic or character liquid-crystal displays (LCD) with a simple menu system.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] More sophisticated devices that use a graphical screen with touch sensing or screen-edge soft keys provide flexibility while minimizing space used: the meaning of the buttons can change with the screen, and selection involves the natural behavior of pointing at what is desired.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Some systems provide user interface remotely with the help of a serial (e.g.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] This approach extends the capabilities of the embedded system, avoids the cost of a display, simplifies the board support package (BSP) and allows designers to build a rich user interface on the PC.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] A good example of this is the combination of an embedded HTTP server running on an embedded device (such as an IP camera or a network router).
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The user interface is displayed in a web browser on a PC connected to the device.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Examples of properties of typical embedded computers when compared with general-purpose counterparts are low power consumption, small size, rugged operating ranges, and low per-unit cost.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] This comes at the expense of limited processing resources.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Numerous microcontrollers have been developed for embedded systems use.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] General-purpose microprocessors are also used in embedded systems, but generally require more support circuitry than microcontrollers.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] PC/104 and PC/104+ are examples of standards for ready-made computer boards intended for small, low-volume embedded and ruggedized systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] These are mostly x86-based and often physically small compared to a standard PC, although still large compared to most simple (8/16-bit) embedded systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] They may use a standard operating system such as Linux or NetBSD or an embedded real-time operating system (RTOS) such as MicroC/OS-II, QNX or VxWorks.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In certain applications, where small size or power efficiency are not primary concerns, the components used may be compatible with those used in general-purpose x86 personal computers.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Boards such as the VIA EPIA range help to bridge the gap by being PC-compatible but highly integrated, physically smaller or have other attributes making them attractive to embedded engineers.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The advantage of this approach is that low-cost commodity components may be used along with the same software development tools used for general software development.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Systems built in this way are still regarded as embedded since they are integrated into larger devices and fulfill a single role.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Examples of devices that may adopt this approach are automated teller machines (ATM) and arcade machines, which contain code specific to the application.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] However, most ready-made embedded systems boards are not PC-centered and do not use the ISA or PCI buses.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] When a system-on-a-chip processor is involved, there may be little benefit to having a standardized bus connecting discrete components, and the environment for both hardware and software tools may be very different.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] One common design style uses a small system module, perhaps the size of a business card, holding high density BGA chips such as an ARM-based system-on-a-chip processor and peripherals, external flash memory for storage, and DRAM for runtime memory.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The module vendor will usually provide boot software and make sure there is a selection of operating systems, usually including Linux and some real-time choices.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] These modules can be manufactured in high volume, by organizations familiar with their specialized testing issues and combined with much lower volume custom mainboards with application-specific external peripherals.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Prominent examples of this approach include Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] A system on a chip (SoC) contains a complete system - consisting of multiple processors, multipliers, caches, even different types of memory and commonly various peripherals like interfaces for wired or wireless communication on a single chip.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Often graphics processing units (GPU) and DSPs are included such chips.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] SoCs can be implemented as an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) or using a field-programmable gate array (FPGA), which typically can be reconfigured.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] ASIC implementations are common for very-high-volume embedded systems like mobile phones and smartphones.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] ASIC or FPGA implementations may be used for not-so-high-volume embedded systems with special needs in terms of signal processing performance, interfaces and reliability, like in avionics.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] As with other software, embedded system designers use compilers, assemblers, and debuggers to develop embedded system software.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Embedded software often requires a variety of development tools, including programming languages such as C++, Rust, or Python, and frameworks like Qt for graphical interfaces.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] These tools enable developers to create efficient, scalable, and feature-rich applications tailored to the specific requirements of embedded systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The choice of tools is driven by factors such as real-time performance, integration with hardware, or energy efficiency.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] As the complexity of embedded systems grows, higher-level tools and operating systems are migrating into machinery where it makes sense.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] For example, cellphones, personal digital assistants and other consumer computers often need significant software that is purchased or provided by a person other than the manufacturer of the electronics.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In these systems, an open programming environment such as Linux, NetBSD, FreeBSD, OSGi or Embedded Java is required so that the third-party software provider can sell to a large market.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Embedded debugging may be performed at different levels, depending on the facilities available.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Unless restricted to external debugging, the programmer can typically load and run software through the tools, view the code running in the processor, and start or stop its operation.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The view of the code may be as high-level programming language, assembly code or a mixture of both.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Real-time operating systems often support tracing of operating system events.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] A graphical view is presented by a host PC tool, based on a recording of the system behavior.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The trace recording can be performed in software, by the RTOS, or by special tracing hardware.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] RTOS tracing allows developers to understand timing and performance issues of the software system and gives a good understanding of the high-level system behaviors.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Trace recording in embedded systems can be achieved using hardware or software solutions.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Software-based trace recording does not require specialized debugging hardware and can be used to record traces in deployed devices, but it can have an impact on CPU and RAM usage.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] One example of a software-based tracing method used in RTOS environments is the use of empty macros which are invoked by the operating system at strategic places in the code, and can be implemented to serve as hooks.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Embedded systems often reside in machines that are expected to run continuously for years without error, and in some cases, recover by themselves if an error occurs.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Therefore, the software is usually developed and tested more carefully than that for personal computers, and unreliable mechanical moving parts such as disk drives, switches or buttons are avoided.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] For high-volume systems such as mobile phones, minimizing cost is usually the primary design consideration.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Engineers typically select hardware that is just good enough to implement the necessary functions.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] For low-volume or prototype embedded systems, general-purpose computers may be adapted by limiting the programs or by replacing the operating system with an RTOS.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In 1978 National Electrical Manufacturers Association released ICS 3-1978, a standard for programmable microcontrollers, including almost any computer-based controllers, such as single-board computers, numerical, and event-based controllers.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] There are several different types of software architecture in common use.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In this design, the software simply has a loop which monitors the input devices.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The loop calls subroutines, each of which manages a part of the hardware or software.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Hence it is called a simple control loop or programmed input-output.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are predominantly controlled by interrupts.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] This means that tasks performed by the system are triggered by different kinds of events; an interrupt could be generated, for example, by a timer at a predefined interval, or by a serial port controller receiving data.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] This architecture is used if event handlers need low latency, and the event handlers are short and simple.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] These systems run a simple task in a main loop also, but this task is not very sensitive to unexpected delays.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Sometimes the interrupt handler will add longer tasks to a queue structure.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Later, after the interrupt handler has finished, these tasks are executed by the main loop.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] This method brings the system close to a multitasking kernel with discrete processes.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Cooperative multitasking is very similar to the simple control loop scheme, except that the loop is hidden in an API.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The programmer defines a series of tasks, and each task gets its own environment to run in.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] When a task is idle, it calls an idle routine, which passes control to another task.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The advantages and disadvantages are similar to those of the control loop, except that adding new software is easier, by simply writing a new task, or adding to the queue.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In this type of system, a low-level piece of code switches between tasks or threads based on a timer that invokes an interrupt.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] This is the level at which the system is generally considered to have an operating system kernel.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Depending on how much functionality is required, it introduces more or less of the complexities associated with managing multiple tasks running conceptually in parallel.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Because of these complexities, it is common for organizations to use an off-the-shelf RTOS, allowing the application programmers to concentrate on device functionality rather than operating system services.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The choice to include an RTOS brings in its own issues, however, as the selection must be made prior to starting the application development process.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] This timing forces developers to choose the embedded operating system for their device based on current requirements and so restricts future options to a large extent.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] These trends are leading to the uptake of embedded middleware in addition to an RTOS.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] A microkernel allocates memory and switches the CPU to different threads of execution.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] User-mode processes implement major functions such as file systems, network interfaces, etc.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Exokernels communicate efficiently by normal subroutine calls.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] The hardware and all the software in the system are available to and extensible by application programmers.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] A monolithic kernel is a relatively large kernel with sophisticated capabilities adapted to suit an embedded environment.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] This gives programmers an environment similar to a desktop operating system like Linux or Microsoft Windows, and is therefore very productive for development.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] On the downside, it requires considerably more hardware resources, is often more expensive, and, because of the complexity of these kernels, can be less predictable and reliable.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Common examples of embedded monolithic kernels are embedded Linux, VXWorks and Windows CE.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] Despite the increased cost in hardware, this type of embedded system is increasing in popularity, especially on the more powerful embedded devices such as wireless routers and GPS navigation systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In addition to the core operating system, many embedded systems have additional upper-layer software components.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] These components include networking protocol stacks like CAN, TCP/IP, FTP, HTTP, and HTTPS, and storage capabilities like FAT and flash memory management systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] If the embedded device has audio and video capabilities, then the appropriate drivers and codecs will be present in the system.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In the case of the monolithic kernels, many of these software layers may be included in the kernel.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In the RTOS category, the availability of additional software components depends on the commercial offering.
[src:vxworks-deep/embedded-system] In the automotive sector, AUTOSAR is a standard architecture for embedded software.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] A **Mars rover** is a remote-controlled motor vehicle designed to travel on the surface of Mars.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] Rovers have several advantages over stationary landers: they examine more territory, they can be directed to interesting features, they can place themselves in sunny positions to weather winter months, and they can advance the knowledge of how to perform very remote robotic vehicle control.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] They serve a different purpose than orbital spacecraft like *Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter*.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] A more recent development is the Mars helicopter.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] The sixth, managed by the China National Space Administration, is *Zhurong* (2021–2022).
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] The search for evidence of habitability, taphonomy (related to fossils), and organic carbon on Mars has become a primary NASA objective.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] The Soviet probes, Mars 2 and Mars 3, were physically tethered probes; *Sojourner* was dependent on the *Mars Pathfinder* base station for communication with Earth; *Opportunity*, *Spirit* and *Curiosity* were on their own.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] As of March 20, 2026, *Curiosity* is still active, while *Spirit*, *Opportunity*, and *Sojourner* completed their missions before losing contact.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] On February 18, 2021, *Perseverance*, the newest American Mars rover, successfully landed.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] On May 14, 2021, China's *Zhurong* became the first non-American rover to successfully operate on Mars.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] Circa the 2010s, NASA had established certain goals for the rover program.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] NASA distinguishes between "mission" objectives and "science" objectives.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] Mission objectives are related to progress in space technology and development processes.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] Science objectives are met by the instruments during their mission in space.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] The science instruments are chosen and designed based on the science objectives and goals.
[src:vxworks-deep/mars-rover] The primary goal of the *Spirit* and *Opportunity* rovers was to investigate "the history of water on Mars".
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:vxworks-deep/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] VxWorks supports AMD/Intel architecture, POWER architecture, ARM architectures, and RISC-V.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The RTOS can be used in multicore asymmetric multiprocessing (AMP), symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), and mixed modes and multi-OS (via Type 1 hypervisor) designs on 32- and 64-bit processors.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] VxWorks comes with the kernel, middleware, board support packages, Wind River Workbench development suite, complementary third-party software and hardware.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] In its latest release, VxWorks 7, the RTOS has been re-engineered for modularity and upgradeability so the OS kernel is separate from middleware, applications, and other packages.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Scalability, security, safety, connectivity, and graphics have been improved to address Internet of Things (IOT) needs.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] VxWorks started in the late 1980s as a set of enhancements to a simple RTOS called VRTX sold by Ready Systems (becoming a Mentor Graphics product in 1995).
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Wind River acquired rights to distribute VRTX and significantly enhanced it by adding, among other things, a file system and an integrated development environment.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] In 1987, anticipating the termination of its reseller contract by Ready Systems, Wind River proceeded to develop its own kernel to replace VRTX within VxWorks.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Published in 2003 with a Wind River copyright, "Real-Time Concepts for Embedded Systems" describes the development environment, runtime setting, and system call families of the RTOS.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Written by Wind River employees with a foreword by Jerry Fiddler, chairman, and co-founder of Wind River, the textbook is an excellent tutorial on the RTOS.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] VxWorks supports Intel architecture, Power architecture, and ARM architectures.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The RTOS can be used in multi-core asymmetric multiprocessing (AMP), symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), mixed modes and multi-OS (via Type 1 hypervisor) designs on 32- and 64- bit processors.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The VxWorks consists of a set of runtime components and development tools.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] VxWorks core development tools are compilers such as Diab, GNU, and Intel C++ Compiler (ICC) and its build and configuration tools.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The system also includes productivity tools such as its Workbench development suite and Intel tools and development support tools for asset tracking and host support.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The platform is a modular, vendor-neutral, open system that supports a range of third-party software and hardware.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The OS kernel is separate from middleware, applications, and other packages, which enables easier bug fixes and testing of new features.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] An implementation of a layered source build system allows multiple versions of any stack to be installed at the same time so developers can select which version of any feature set should go into the VxWorks kernel libraries.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] In March 2014 Wind River introduced VxWorks 7, emphasizing scalability, security, safety, connectivity, graphics, and virtualization.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The following lists some of the release 7 updates.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] More information can be found on the Wind Rivers VxWorks website.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] VxWorks has been ported to a number of platforms.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] This includes the Intel x86 family (including the Intel Quark SoC), MIPS, PowerPC (and BAE RAD), Freescale ColdFire, Intel i960, SPARC, Fujitsu FR-V, SH-4 and the closely related family of ARM, StrongARM and xScale CPUs.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] VxWorks provides a standard board support package (BSP) interface between all its supported hardware and the OS.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Wind River's BSP developer kit provides a common application programming interface (API) and a stable environment for real-time operating system development.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] VxWorks is supported by popular SSL/TLS libraries such as wolfSSL.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] As is common in embedded system development, cross-compiling is used with VxWorks.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Development is done on a "host" system where an integrated development environment (IDE), including the editor, compiler toolchain, debugger, and emulator can be used.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Software is then compiled to run on the "target" system.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] This allows the developer to work with powerful development tools while targeting more limited hardware.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] VxWorks supports a range of target architectures including ARM, Intel, Power architecture, RISC-V architecture and more.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] For the latest target architecture processors and board support packages, refer to the VxWorks Marketplace or via citation.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The Eclipse-based Workbench IDE that comes with VxWorks is used to configure, analyze, optimize, and debug a VxWorks-based system under development.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The *Tornado* IDE was used for VxWorks 5.x and was replaced by the Eclipse-based *Workbench* IDE for VxWorks 6.x. and later.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Workbench is also the IDE for the Wind River Linux, On-Chip Debugging, and Wind River Diab Compiler product lines.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] VxWorks 7 uses Wind River Workbench 4 which updates to the Eclipse 4 base provides full third party plug-in support and usability improvements.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Wind River Simics is a standalone simulation tool compatible with VxWorks.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] It simulates the full target system (hardware and software) to create a shared platform for software development.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Multiple developers can share a complete virtual system and its entire state, including execution history.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Simics enables early and continuous system integration and faster prototyping by utilizing virtual prototypes instead of physical prototypes.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] VxWorks is used by products across a wide range of market areas: aerospace and defense, automotive, industrial such as robots, consumer electronics, medical area and networking.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] Several notable products also use VxWorks as the onboard operating system.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] As of July 2019, a paper published by Armis exposed 11 critical vulnerabilities, including remote code execution, denial of service, information leaks, and logical flaws impacting more than two billion devices using the VxWorks RTOS.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The vulnerability allows attackers to tunnel into an *internal* network using the vulnerability and hack into printers, laptops, and any other connected devices.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The vulnerability can bypass firewalls as well.
[src:vxworks-deep/vxworks] The system is in use by quite a few mission-critical products, many of which could not be easily patched.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Wind River Systems was formed by a partnership of Jerry Fiddler and Dave Wilner.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Until 1981, Fiddler had worked at Berkeley Lab writing software for control systems, and wanted to pursue a career in computer generated music, which he funded through a consultancy business focused on real-time operating systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] His early clients included the National Football League and film director Francis Ford Coppola, for whom he designed a unique film editing system.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Wilner, a former colleague at Berkeley Lab, joined Fiddler to form Wind River Systems in 1983.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] In 2009, Wind River was acquired by Intel.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] In 2018, Intel spun out its Wind River division, which was then acquired by TPG Capital.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] On January 11, 2022, Wind River announced that it was acquired by Aptiv, an auto parts company, for $4.3 billion in cash.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Among the company's products are the VxWorks real-time operating system, the Wind River Linux operating system, and the Eclipse-based Wind River Workbench IDE.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] VxWorks began as an add-on to the VRTX operating system in the early 1980s.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Wind River Workbench superseded the previous *Tornado* environment.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] VxWorks is the original flagship product of Wind River.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] It is a real-time operating system (RTOS) intended for embedded and critical infrastructure devices and systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] It supports multicore processors, 32-bit and 64-bit, for several architectures including ARM, Intel, and Power and has over one hundred board support packages (BSPs) for different hardware systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] VxWorks is a real time and deterministic operating system.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Wind River's Linux product is source code and a build system that generate runtime images suitable for embedded devices.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Historically, Wind River Linux has supported a variety of architectures, including ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, IA32 and SPARC.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] The current release of Wind River Linux supports a variety of ARM, IA32, and IA64 platforms with both standard and realtime (PREEMPT RT) kernels.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Wind River charges a subscription to provide commercial bug and CVE fixes for its Linux products.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Pricing is project-based, with a flat fee for each solution built on top of Wind River Linux.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] There is no per-device subscription or royalty.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] The key capabilities for Wind River Linux are 10 year commercial support life, complete customization including kernel changes, reproducible customizations, wide range of hardware support through Board Support Packages (BSP) that are ported, maintained, and tested by Wind River.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] In 2004, Wind River announced a partnership with Red Hat to create a new Linux-based distribution for embedded devices.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Wind River has since ended its partnership with Red Hat and now ships its own Linux distribution optimized for embedded Linux development.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Wind River released the first version of its embedded Linux distribution, Platform for Network Equipment - Linux Edition (PNE-LE) 1.0 in 2005.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] It was registered against the Carrier Grade Linux 2.0 specification and supported IA32 and PPC architectures.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] They added other platforms in subsequent releases, General Purpose Platform - Linux Edition (GPP-LE) and Platform for Consumer Devices - Linux Edition PCD-LE) starting in version 1.4.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] In 2013 Wind River announced Wind River Linux 6.0.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Wind River Systems acquired FSMLabs embedded technology in February 2007 and made a version available as Wind River Real-Time Core for Wind River Linux.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] As of August 2011, Wind River has discontinued the Wind River Real-Time Core product line, effectively ending commercial support for the RTLinux product.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] On August 7, 2007, Palm Inc. announced it would use Wind River Systems Linux for its (later aborted) Palm Foleo.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] In 2008, Wind River announced cooperation with BMW, Intel and Magneti Marelli for development of a Linux-based open-source platform to control in-car electronics, which was extended in the GENIVI Alliance in 2009.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] In 2012, Wind River introduced a version of Linux that was developed from the Yocto Project open source development infrastructure and achieved Yocto project compatible registration.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] All subsequent releases of Wind River Linux are based on the Yocto Project.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Wind River has historically released a new Wind River Linux LTS (Long Term Support) about every year that are generally based on the then current Linux Kernel LTS release and the latest Yocto Project release.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] In 2022, Wind River launched a new product, Wind River Linux Distro, that is a binary Linux distribution based on the Wind River Linux source-based product.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] The Distro is intended for embedded solution developers that need a commercially supported Linux for their project, but do not need the extensive customization capabilities of the Yocto Project-based Wind River Linux.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] The key features are quick time to value, customization via tools such as the Linux Assembly Tool & an RPM package feed, and updates via OSTree.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] A number of hardware platforms are enabled by the Distro.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Commercial support is currently available for a subset of the enabled platforms.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Simics is a full-system simulator used by software developers to simulate the hardware of complex electronic systems.
[src:vxworks-deep/wind-river-systems] Wind River Studio is a cloud-native platform for the deployment and servicing of mission-critical intelligent edge systems.
